[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] `import {rollup} from 'rollup'`, via a `/node_modules/` regular expression, you need something like @rollup/plugin-node-resolve to resolve the imports to `node_modules` first.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] When creating an `iife` or `umd` bundle, you will need to provide global variable names to replace your external imports via the `output.globals` option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] Note that source phase imports (`import source x from 'y'`) are required to be external.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] Rollup will raise an error if a source phase import resolves to a module that is not external.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] If a relative import, i.e. starting with `./` or `../`, is marked as "external", rollup will internally resolve the id to an absolute file system location so that different imports of the external module can be merged.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] When the resulting bundle is written, the import will again be converted to a relative import.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] The conversion back to a relative import is done as if `output.file` or `output.dir` were in the same location as the entry point or the common base directory of all entry points if there is more than one.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] The bundle's entry point(s) (e.g. your `main.js` or `app.js` or `index.js`).
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] If you provide an array of entry points or an object mapping names to entry points, they will be bundled to separate output chunks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] Unless the `output.file` option is used, generated chunk names will follow the `output.entryFileNames` option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] When using the object form, the `[name]` portion of the file name will be the name of the object property while for the array form, it will be the file name of the entry point.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] Note that it is possible when using the object form to put entry points into different sub-folders by adding a `/` to the name.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p01] If you want to convert a set of files to another format while maintaining the file structure and export signatures, the recommended way—instead of using `output.preserveModules` that may tree-shake exports as well as emit virtual files created by plugins—is to turn every file into an entry point.
