[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] The `cache` property of a previous bundle.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Use it to speed up subsequent builds in watch mode — Rollup will only reanalyse the modules that have changed.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Setting this option explicitly to `false` will prevent generating the `cache` property on the bundle and also deactivate caching for plugins.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See `onLog` for the available log levels.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] The default `logLevel` of `"info"` means that info and warnings logs will be processed while debug logs will be swallowed, which means that they are neither passed to plugin `onLog` hooks nor the `onLog` option or printed to the console.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] When using the CLI, errors will still be printed to the console as they are not processed via the logging system.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See the `--silent` flag for how to suppress error logs.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Determines if absolute external paths should be converted to relative paths in the output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This does not only apply to paths that are absolute in the source but also to paths that are resolved to an absolute path by either a plugin or Rollup core.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] For `true`, an external import like `import "/Users/Rollup/project/relative.js"` would be converted to a relative path.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] When converting an absolute path to a relative path, Rollup does *not* take the `file` or `dir` options into account, because those may not be present e.g. for builds using the JavaScript API.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Instead, it assumes that the root of the generated bundle is located at the common shared parent directory of all modules that were included in the bundle.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Assuming that the common parent directory of all modules is `"/Users/Rollup/project"`, the import from above would likely be converted to `import "./relative.js"` in the output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] If the output chunk is itself nested in a subdirectory by choosing e.g.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] `chunkFileNames: "chunks/[name].js"`, the import would be `"../relative.js"`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] As stated before, this would also apply to originally relative imports like `import "./relative.js"` that are resolved to an absolute path before they are marked as external by the `external` option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] One common problem is that this mechanism will also apply to imports like `import "/absolute.js'"`, resulting in unexpected relative paths in the output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] For this case, `"ifRelativeSource"` checks if the original import was a relative import and only then convert it to a relative import in the output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Choosing `false` will keep all paths as absolute paths in the output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note that when a relative path is directly marked as "external" using the `external` option, then it will be the same relative path in the output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] When it is resolved first via a plugin or Rollup core and then marked as external, the above logic will apply.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Limits the number of files rollup will open in parallel when reading modules or writing chunks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Without a limit or with a high enough value, builds can fail with an "EMFILE: too many open files".
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This depends on how many open file handles the operating system allows.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] If you set the limit too low and use plugins that rely on the `this.load` context function, such as the `commonjs` plugin, then it can happen that builds stall without an error message as it limits the number of parallel `load` calls.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] A function that intercepts log messages.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] If not supplied, logs are printed to the console, whereby Rollup CLI aggregates certain `"warn"` logs and prints consolidated warnings after the build to reduce noise.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This handler is also triggered when using the `--silent` CLI option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] The function receives three arguments: the log level, the log object and the default handler.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Log objects have, at a minimum, a `code` and a `message` property, allowing you to control how different kinds of logs are handled.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Other properties are added depending on the type of log.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See `utils/logs.ts` for a complete list of built-in errors and logs together with their codes and properties.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] If the default handler is not invoked, the log will not be printed to the console.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Moreover, you can change the log level by invoking the default handler with a different level.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Using the additional level `"error"` will turn the log into a thrown error that has all properties of the log attached.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This handler will not be invoked if logs are filtered out by the `logLevel` option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] I.e. by default, `"debug"` logs will be swallowed.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] A function that will intercept warning messages.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] It is very similar to `onLog` but only receives warnings.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] If the default handler is invoked, the log will be handled as a warning.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] If both an `onLog` and `onwarn` handler are provided, the `onwarn` handler will only be invoked if `onLog` calls its default handler with a `level` of `warn`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] The pattern to use for naming custom emitted assets to include in the build output, or a function that is called per asset to return such a pattern.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Forward slashes `/` can be used to place files in sub-directories.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] When using a function, `PreRenderedAsset` is a reduced version of the `OutputAsset` type in `generateBundle` without the `fileName`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See also `output.chunkFileNames`, `output.entryFileNames`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See the `renderChunk` hook for the `RenderedChunk` type.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] A string to prepend/append to the bundle.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] You can also supply a function that returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `string` to generate it asynchronously (Note: `banner` and `footer` options will not break sourcemaps).
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] `chunk` is mutable and changes applied in this hook will propagate to other plugins and to the generated bundle.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] That means if you add or remove imports or exports in this hook, you should update `imports`, `importedBindings` and/or `exports`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] The pattern to use for naming shared chunks created when code-splitting, or a function that is called per chunk to return such a pattern.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] When using a function, `PreRenderedChunk` is a reduced version of the `OutputChunk` type in `generateBundle` without properties that depend on file names and no information about the rendered modules as rendering only happens after file names have been generated.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] You can however access a list of included `moduleIds`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See also `output.assetFileNames`, `output.entryFileNames`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This will minify the wrapper code generated by rollup.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note that this does not affect code written by the user.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This option is useful when bundling pre-minified code.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] While CommonJS output originally supported only `require(…)` to import dependencies, recent Node versions also started to support `import(…)`, which is the only way to import ES modules from CommonJS files.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] If this option is `true`, which is the default, Rollup will keep external dynamic imports as `import(…)` expressions in CommonJS output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Set this to `false` to rewrite dynamic imports using `require(…)` syntax.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See `output.chunkFileNames` for the `PreRenderedChunk` type.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] The pattern to use for chunks created from entry points, or a function that is called per entry chunk to return such a pattern.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See also `output.assetFileNames`, `output.chunkFileNames`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This pattern will also be used for every file when setting the `output.preserveModules` option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note that in this case, `[name]` will include the relative path from the output root and possibly the original file extension if it was not one of `.js`, `.jsx`, `.mjs`, `.cjs`, `.ts`, `.tsx`, `.mts`, or `.cts`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Whether to extend the global variable defined by the `name` option in `umd` or `iife` formats.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] When `true`, the global variable will be defined as `(global.name = global.name || {})`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] When false, the global defined by `name` will be overwritten like `(global.name = {})`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Whether to add import attributes to external imports in the output if the output format is `es` or `cjs`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] By default, attributes are taken from the input files, but plugins can add or remove attributes later.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] `import "foo" assert {type: "json"}` will cause the same import to appear in the output unless the option is set to `false`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note that all imports of a module need to have consistent attributes, otherwise a warning is emitted.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Which language features Rollup can safely use in generated code.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This will not transpile any user code but only change the code Rollup uses in wrappers and helpers.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Whether to use arrow functions for auto-generated code snippets.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note that in certain places like module wrappers, Rollup will keep using regular functions wrapped in parentheses as in some JavaScript engines, these will provide noticeably better performance.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This will use `const` instead of `var` in certain places and helper functions.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This will allow Rollup to generate more efficient helpers due to block scoping.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Allows the use of shorthand notation in objects when the property name matches the value.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Determine whether reserved words like "default" can be used as prop names without using quotes.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This will make the syntax of the generated code ES3 compliant.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note however that for full ES3 compliance, you may also need to polyfill some builtin functions like `Object.keys` or `Array.prototype.forEach`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Whether to allow the use of `Symbol` in auto-generated code snippets.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Currently, this only controls if namespaces will have the `Symbol.toStringTag` property set to the correct value of `Module`, which means that for a namespace, `String(namespace)` logs `[object Module]`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This again is used for feature detection in certain libraries and frameworks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This determines the character set that Rollup is allowed to use in file hashes.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] By default, when creating multiple chunks, transitive imports of entry chunks will be added as empty imports to the entry chunks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] See "Why do additional imports turn up in my entry chunks when code-splitting?" for details and background.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Setting this option to `false` will disable this behaviour.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This option is ignored when using the `output.preserveModules` option as here, imports will never be hoisted.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This determines the keyword set that Rollup will use for import attributes.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] This will inline dynamic imports instead of creating new chunks to create a single bundle.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Only possible if a single input is provided.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note that this will change the execution order: A module that is only imported dynamically will be executed immediately if the dynamic import is inlined.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Controls how Rollup handles default, namespace and dynamic imports from external dependencies in formats like CommonJS that do not natively support these concepts.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Note that the default mode of "default" mimics NodeJS behavior and is different from TypeScript `esModuleInterop`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] To get TypeScript's behavior, explicitly set the value to `"auto"`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] In the examples, we will be using the CommonJS format, but the choice of interop similarly applies to AMD, IIFE and UMD targets as well.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] Keep in mind that for Rollup, `import * as ext_namespace from 'external'; console.log(ext_namespace.bar);` is completely equivalent to `import {bar} from 'external'; console.log(bar);` and will produce the same code.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p02] In the example above however, the namespace object itself is passed to a global function as well, which means we need it as a properly formed object.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Similar to `output.banner/output.footer`, except that the code goes *inside* any format-specific wrapper.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Allows the creation of custom shared common chunks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The object form can be used for an easier and safer manual chunking, and the function form can be used for a more powerful and controlled behavior.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When using the object form, each property represents a chunk that contains the listed modules and all their dependencies if they are part of the module graph unless they are already in another manual chunk.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The name of the chunk will be determined by the property key.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note that it is not necessary for the listed modules themselves to be part of the module graph, which is useful if you are working with `@rollup/plugin-node-resolve` and use deep imports from packages.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] will merge all lodash modules into a manual chunk even if you are only using imports of the form `import get from 'lodash/get'`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When using the function form, each resolved module id will be passed to the function.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If a string is returned, the module and all its dependencies will be added to the manual chunk with the given name.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] By default, the function form will also merge dependencies of the returned ids into the manualChunk.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If you need stricter behavior, you can use output.onlyExplicitManualChunks, which will be the default in Rollup 5.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Be aware that manual chunks can change the behaviour of the application if side effects are triggered before the corresponding modules are actually used.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When using the function form, `manualChunks` will be passed an object as second parameter containing the functions `getModuleInfo` and `getModuleIds` that work the same way as `this.getModuleInfo` and `this.getModuleIds` on the plugin context.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This can be used to dynamically determine into which manual chunk a module should be placed depending on its position in the module graph.
