[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If a lot of such components are used together, this will result in a lot of dynamic imports of very small chunks: Even though we know that all language files of the same language that are imported by the same chunk will always be used together, Rollup does not have this information.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] By default, for formats `es` and `system` or if `output.compact` is `true`, Rollup will try to export internal variables as single letter variables to allow for better minification.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Even though it appears that setting this option to `true` makes the output larger, it actually makes it smaller if a minifier is used.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] In this case, `export { importantValue as i }` can become e.g.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] `export{a as i}` or even `export{i}`, while otherwise it would produce `export{ a as importantValue }` because a minifier usually will not change export signatures.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] External ids are ids that cannot be resolved or ids explicitly provided by the `external` option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Instead of creating as few chunks as possible, this mode will create separate chunks for all modules using the original module names as file names.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Tree-shaking will still be applied, suppressing files that are not used by the provided entry points or do not have side effects when executed and removing unused exports of files that are not entry points.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] On the other hand, if plugins (like `@rollup/plugin-commonjs`) emit additional "virtual" files to achieve certain results, those files will be emitted as actual files using a pattern `${output.virtualDirname}/fileName.js`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] It is therefore not recommended to blindly use this option to transform an entire file structure to another format if you directly want to import from those files as expected exports may be missing.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] In that case, you should rather designate all files explicitly as entry points by adding them to the `input` option object, see the example there for how to do that.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note that when transforming to `cjs` or `amd` format, each file will by default be treated as an entry point with `output.exports` set to `auto`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] assigning the value directly to `module.exports`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] As with regular entry points, files that mix default and named exports will produce warnings.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] You can avoid the warnings by forcing all files to use named export mode via `output.exports: "named"`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] A directory path to input modules that should be stripped away from `output.dir` path while `output.preserveModules` is `true`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The `preserveModulesRoot` setting ensures that the input modules will be output to the paths `dist/module.js` and `dist/another/module.js`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This option is particularly useful while using plugins such as `@rollup/plugin-node-resolve`, which may cause changes in the output directory structure.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This can happen when third-party modules are not marked `external`, or while developing in a monorepo of multiple packages that rely on one another and are not marked `external`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If `true`, a separate sourcemap file will be created.
