[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This can be useful to debug output generated by plugins that use the `renderChunk` hook to transform code.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If the code is invalid, a warning will be issued.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note that no error is thrown so that you can still inspect the generated output.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] To promote this warning to an error, you can watch for it in an `onwarn` handler.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This option specifies the directory name for "virtual" files that might be emitted by plugins (like `@rollup/plugin-commonjs`).
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] It is only validated when `output.preserveModules` is enabled.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Controls if Rollup tries to ensure that entry chunks have the same exports as the underlying entry module.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] At the moment, the only way to override this setting for individual entry chunks is to use the plugin API and emit those chunks via `this.emitFile` instead of using the `input` option.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When this flag is enabled, Rollup will throw an error instead of showing a warning when a deprecated feature is used.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Furthermore, features that are marked to receive a deprecation warning with the next major version will also throw an error when used.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This flag is intended to be used by e.g. plugin authors to be able to adjust their plugins for upcoming major releases as early as possible.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] You probably don't need to use these options unless you know what you are doing!
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] By default, the context of a module – i.e., the value of `this` at the top level – is `undefined`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] In rare cases you might need to change this to something else, like `'window'`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Same as `context`, but per-module – can either be an object of `id: context` pairs, or an `id => context` function.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note `id` can only be used for single-file builds, and cannot be combined with `autoId`/`basePath`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Set the ID to the chunk ID (with the '.js' extension removed).
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The path that will be prepended to the auto generated ID.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This is useful if the build is going to be placed inside another AMD project, and is not at the root.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Whether to add a `__esModule: true` property when generating exports for non-ES formats.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This property signifies that the exported value is the namespace of an ES module and that the default export of this module corresponds to the `.default` property of the exported object.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] As this is only an output transformation, you can only choose `default` if a default export is the only export for all entry chunks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Likewise, you can only choose `none` if there are no exports, otherwise Rollup will throw an error.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The difference between `default` and `named` affects how other people can consume your bundle.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note: There are some tools such as Babel, TypeScript, Webpack, and `@rollup/plugin-commonjs` that are capable of resolving a CommonJS `require(...)` call with an ES module.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If you are generating CommonJS output that is meant to be interchangeable with ESM output for those tools, you should always use `named` export mode.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The reason is that most of those tools will by default return the namespace of an ES module on `require` where the default export is the `.default` property.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] In other words for those tools, you cannot create a package interface where `const lib = require("your-lib")` yields the same as `import lib from "your-lib"`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] With named export mode however, `const {lib} = require("your-lib")` will be equivalent to `import {lib} from "your-lib"`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When set to `false`, Rollup will not generate code to support live bindings for external imports but instead assume that exports do not change over time.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This will enable Rollup to generate more optimized code.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note that this can cause issues when there are circular dependencies involving an external dependency.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This will avoid most cases where Rollup generates getters in the code and can therefore be used to make code IE8 compatible in many cases.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Whether to `Object.freeze()` namespace import objects (i.e.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] `import * as namespaceImportObject from...`) that are accessed dynamically.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The indent string to use, for formats that require code to be indented (`amd`, `iife`, `umd`, `system`).
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This will generate an additional `noConflict` export to UMD bundles.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When called in an IIFE scenario, this method will return the bundle exports while restoring the corresponding global variable to its previous value.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This option is only effective when `output.format` is set to one of `['amd', 'cjs', 'iife', 'umd']` and `output.externalLiveBindings` is set to false.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] For maximum compatibility, Rollup reexports `__proto__` from an external module by default.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] However, for common use cases, it is strongly recommended to set this value to false as it effectively reduces the output size.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Set to `false` to disable all chunk name sanitizations (removal of `\0`, `?` and `*` characters).
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Alternatively set to a function to allow custom chunk name sanitization.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Whether to include the 'use strict' pragma at the top of generated non-ES bundles.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Strictly speaking, ES modules are *always* in strict mode, so you shouldn't disable this without good reason.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When outputting the `system` module format, by default, empty setter functions are replaced with `null` as an output simplification.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This is incompatible with SystemJS before v6.3.3.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Deactivate this option to output empty functions instead that older SystemJS versions support.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When set to `false`, symbolic links are followed when resolving a file.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When set to `true`, instead of being followed, symbolic links are treated as if the file is where the link is.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If `preserveSymlinks` is `false`, then the bundle created from `/main.js` will log "next to original" as it will use the location of the symbolically linked file to resolve its dependencies.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If `preserveSymlinks` is `true`, however, it will log "next to linked" as the symbolic link will not be resolved.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If this option is provided, bundling will not fail if bindings are imported from a file that does not define these bindings.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Instead, new variables will be created for these bindings with the value `undefined`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Whether to apply tree-shaking and to fine-tune the tree-shaking process.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Setting this option to `false` will produce bigger bundles but may improve build performance.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If you discover a bug caused by the tree-shaking algorithm, please file an issue!
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Comments containing `@__PURE__` or `#__PURE__` mark a specific function call or constructor invocation as side effect free.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] That means that Rollup will tree-shake i.e. remove the call unless the return value is used in some code that is not tree-shaken.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] These annotations need to immediately precede the call invocation to take effect.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The following code will be completely tree-shaken unless this option is set to `false`, in which case it will remain unchanged.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Such an annotation is considered *valid* if it directly precedes a function call or constructor invocation and is only separated from the callee by white-space or comments.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] The only exception are parentheses that wrap a call or invocation.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Invalid annotations are removed and Rollup emits a warning.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Valid annotations remain in the code unless their function call or constructor invocation is removed as well.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Comments containing `@__NO_SIDE_EFFECTS__` or `#__NO_SIDE_EFFECTS__` mark a function declaration itself as side effect free.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] When a function has been marked as having no side effects, all calls to that function will be considered to be side effect free.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Such an annotation is considered *valid* if it directly precedes a function declaration or a constant variable declaration where the first declared variable is a function and is only separated from the declaration by white-space or comments.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] In some edge cases if a variable is accessed before its declaration assignment and is not reassigned, then Rollup may incorrectly assume that variable is constant throughout the program, as in the example below.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This is not true if the variable is declared with `var`, however, as those variables can be accessed before their declaration where they will evaluate to `undefined`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Choosing `true` will make sure Rollup does not make any assumptions about the value of variables declared with `var`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note though that this can have a noticeable negative impact on tree-shaking results.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Allows to manually define a list of function names that should always be considered "pure", i.e. they have no side effects like changing global state etc. when called.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This can not only help with dead code removal, but can also improve JavaScript chunk generation especially when using `output.experimentalMinChunkSize`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Besides any functions matching that name, any properties on a pure function and any functions returned from a pure functions will also be considered pure functions, and accessing any properties is not checked for side effects.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If you pass arguments to such a pure function, those arguments are still checked for direct side effects like mutating a variable or calling a global function, in which case the call to the pure function is retained.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] But be aware that we do not check if those arguments are called and whether such a call could have side effects.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If `false`, assume modules and external dependencies from which nothing is imported do not have other side effects like mutating global variables or logging without checking.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] You can also supply a list of modules with side effects or a function to determine it for each module individually.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note that despite the name, this option does not "add" side effects to modules that do not have side effects.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If it is important that e.g. an empty module is "included" in the bundle because you need this for dependency tracking, the plugin interface allows you to designate modules as being excluded from tree-shaking via the `resolveId`, `load` or `transform` hook.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If `true`, retain unused property reads that Rollup can determine to have side effects.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This includes accessing properties of `null` or `undefined` or triggering explicit getters via property access.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Note that this does not cover destructuring assignment or getters on objects passed as function parameters.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If `false`, assume reading a property of an object never has side effects.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Depending on your code, disabling this option can significantly reduce bundle size but can potentially break functionality if you rely on getters or errors from illegal property access.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If `'always'`, assume all member property accesses, including destructuring, have side effects.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This setting is recommended for code relying on getters with side effects.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] It typically results in larger bundle size, but smaller than disabling `treeshake` altogether.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] By default, Rollup assumes that many builtin globals of the runtime behave according to the latest specs when tree-shaking and do not throw unexpected errors.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] In order to support e.g. feature detection workflows that rely on those errors being thrown, Rollup will by default deactivate tree-shaking inside try-statements.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] If a function parameter is called from within a try-statement, this parameter will be deoptimized as well.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Set `treeshake.tryCatchDeoptimization` to `false` if you do not need this feature and want to have tree-shaking inside try-statements.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Since accessing a non-existing global variable will throw an error, Rollup does by default retain any accesses to non-builtin global variables.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] Set this option to `false` to avoid this check.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] This is probably safe for most code-bases.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] In the example, the last line is always retained as accessing the `element` property could also throw an error if `angular` is e.g.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p03] To avoid this check, set `treeshake.propertyReadSideEffects` to `false` as well.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] These options reflect new features that have not yet been fully finalized.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Availability, behaviour and usage may therefore be subject to change between minor versions.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Determines after how many runs cached assets that are no longer used by plugins should be removed.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] When set to `true`, this will log the first side effect it finds in every file to the console.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] This can be very helpful to figure which files have side effects and what the actual side effects are.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Removing side effects can improve tree-shaking and chunk generation and is crucial to make `output.experimentalMinChunkSize` work.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] This option will only log top-level statements, though.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Sometimes, e.g. in case of immediately-invoked-function-expressions, the actual side effect can be hidden inside a nested expression.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Set a minimal chunk size target in Byte for code-splitting setups.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] When this value is set to the default of `1`, Rollup will try to merge chunks that do not contain code except imports and reexports into other chunks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] A merge will only be performed if it does not change what side effects are executed when any entry is loaded.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] For the value of `1`, only merges are permitted that do not increase the amount of code loaded for any entry.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Larger values will try to merge any chunk below the limit into other chunks.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] In that case, it is accepted that entries may load some unnecessary code.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] The algorithm always tries to merge in a way that minimizes the amount of unnecessary code, though.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Unfortunately, due to the way chunking works, chunk size is measured before any chunk rendering plugins like minifiers ran, which means you should use a high enough limit to take this into account.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] It will take tree-shaking of top-level statements into account when calculating the size.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] When used from the command line or a configuration file, detailed measurements about the current bundling process will be displayed.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] When used from the JavaScript API, the returned bundle object will contain an additional `getTimings()` function that can be called at any time to retrieve all accumulated measurements.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] For each key, the first number represents the elapsed time while the second represents the change in memory consumption, and the third represents the total memory consumption after this step.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] The order of these steps is the order used by `Object.keys`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Top level keys start with `#` and contain the timings of nested steps, i.e. in the example above, the 698ms of the `# BUILD` step include the 538ms of the `## parse modules` step.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] If you want to use a custom file system module, you can set this option to an object that implements the same API as the `RollupFsModule` interface.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] This is useful if you want to use a different file system implementation such as `memfs`, if you want to mock the file system for testing purposes, or if you use the browser build of Rollup.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Specify options for watch mode or prevent this configuration from being watched.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Specifying `false` is only really useful when an array of configurations is used.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] These options only take effect when running Rollup with the `--watch` flag, or using `rollup.watch`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Whether the input path is allowed to be a subpath of the output path.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Configures how long Rollup will wait for further changes until it triggers a rebuild in milliseconds.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] By default, Rollup does not wait but there is a small debounce timeout configured in the chokidar instance.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Setting this to a value greater than `0` will mean that Rollup will only trigger a rebuild if there was no change for the configured number of milliseconds.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] If several configurations are watched, Rollup will use the largest configured build delay.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] An optional object of watch options that will be passed to the bundled chokidar instance.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] See the chokidar documentation to find out what options are available.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Whether to clear the screen when a rebuild is triggered.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Limit the file-watching to certain files.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Whether to skip the `bundle.write()` step when a rebuild is triggered.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] An optional function that will be called immediately every time a module changes that is part of the build.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] It receives the id of the changed module as argument.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] This is different from the `watchChange` plugin hook, which is only called once the running build has finished.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] This may for instance be used to prevent additional steps from being performed if we know another build will be started anyway once the current build finished.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] This callback may be called multiple times per build as it tracks every change.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] ☢️ These options have been deprecated and may be removed in a future Rollup version.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Whether to add import assertions to external imports in the output if the output format is `es`.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] By default, assertions are taken from the input files, but plugins can add or remove assertions later.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Note that all imports of a module need to have consistent assertions, otherwise a warning is emitted.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] If set to true, using the output.manualChunks function form won't merge dependencies into the output chunk.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] the dep.js `export const dep = 'dep';` code, won't be merged into the `manual` output chunk.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] This gives you full control over what code goes into which manual chunks, and if your manual chunking is very granular, this can prevent import graph inaccuracies and help reduce cache invalidation.
[src:rollup/configuration-options-p04] Note: although this option is new in Rollup 4, it is marked as deprecated because it will become the new default for the function form in Rollup 5.
[src:rollup/introduction] Rollup is a module bundler for JavaScript which compiles small pieces of code into something larger and more complex, such as a library or application.
[src:rollup/introduction] It uses the new standardized format for code modules included in the ES6 revision of JavaScript, instead of previous idiosyncratic solutions such as CommonJS and AMD.
[src:rollup/introduction] ES modules let you freely and seamlessly combine the most useful individual functions from your favorite libraries.
[src:rollup/introduction] This will eventually be possible natively everywhere, but Rollup lets you do it today.
[src:rollup/introduction] This will make Rollup available as a global command line tool.
[src:rollup/introduction] You can also install it locally, see Installing Rollup locally.
[src:rollup/introduction] Rollup can be used either through a command line interface with an optional configuration file, or else through its JavaScript API.
[src:rollup/introduction] Run `rollup --help` to see the available options and parameters.
[src:rollup/introduction] These commands assume the entry point to your application is named `main.js`, and that you'd like all imports compiled into a single file named `bundle.js`.
[src:rollup/introduction] Unfortunately, JavaScript has not historically included this capability as a core feature in the language.
[src:rollup/introduction] This finally changed with the ES6 revision of JavaScript, which includes a syntax for importing and exporting functions and data so they can be shared between separate scripts.
[src:rollup/introduction] The specification is now fixed, but it is only implemented in modern browsers and not finalised in Node.js.
[src:rollup/introduction] Rollup allows you to write your code using the new module system, and will then compile it back down to existing supported formats such as CommonJS modules, AMD modules, and IIFE-style scripts.
[src:rollup/introduction] In addition to enabling the use of ES modules, Rollup also statically analyzes the code you are importing, and will exclude anything that isn't actually used.
[src:rollup/introduction] This allows you to build on top of existing tools and modules without adding extra dependencies or bloating the size of your project.
[src:rollup/introduction] For example, with CommonJS, the *entire tool or library must be imported*.
[src:rollup/introduction] Because Rollup includes the bare minimum, it results in lighter, faster, and less complicated libraries and applications.
[src:rollup/introduction] Since this approach can utilise explicit `import` and `export` statements, it is more effective than simply running an automated minifier to detect unused variables in the compiled output code.
[src:rollup/introduction] Rollup can import existing CommonJS modules through a plugin.
[src:rollup/introduction] To make sure your ES modules are immediately usable by tools that work with CommonJS such as Node.js and webpack, you can use Rollup to compile to UMD or CommonJS format, and then point to that compiled version with the `main` property in your `package.json` file.
[src:rollup/introduction] If your `package.json` file also has a `module` field, ES-module-aware tools like Rollup and webpack 2+ will import the ES module version directly.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] Minification can be distinguished from the more general concept of data compression in that the minified source can be interpreted immediately without the need for a decompression step: the same interpreter can work with both the original as well as with the minified source.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] The goals of minification are not the same as the goals of obfuscation; the former is often intended to be reversed using a pretty printer or unminifier.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] However, to achieve its goals, minification sometimes uses techniques also used by obfuscation; for example, shortening variable names and refactoring the source code.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] When minification uses such techniques, the pretty-printer or unminifier can only fully reverse the minification process if it is supplied details of the transformations done by such techniques.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] If not supplied those details, the reversed source code will contain different variable names and control flow, even though it will have the same functionality as the original source code.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] In 2001 Douglas Crockford introduced JSMin, which removed comments and whitespace from JavaScript code.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] It was followed by YUI Compressor in 2007.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] In 2009, Google opened up its Closure toolkit, including Closure Compiler which contained a source mapping feature together with a Firefox extension called Closure Inspector.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] In 2010, Mihai Bazon introduced UglifyJS, which was superseded by UglifyJS2 in 2012; the rewrite was to allow for source map support.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] From 2017, Alex Lam took over maintenance and development of UglifyJS2, replacing it with UglifyJS3 which unified the CLI with the API.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] In 2018, Terser has been forked from uglify-es and has gained momentum since; in 2020 it outstripped UglifyJS when measured in daily downloads.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] Since late 2018, Terser has recommended the bundler RollupJS.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] A **source map** is a file format that allows software tools for JavaScript to display different code to a user than the code actually executed by the computer.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] For example, to aid in debugging of minified code, by "mapping" this code to the original unminified source code instead.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] The original format was created by Joseph Schorr as part of the Closure Inspector minification project.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] Version 2 and 3 of the format reduced the size of the map files considerably.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] In 2024, source maps were standardized by Ecma International's TC39 technical committee as ECMA-426.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] JavaScript and Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) resources may be minified, preserving their behavior while considerably reducing their file size.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] Libraries available online are capable of minification and optimization to varying degrees.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] Some libraries also merge multiple script files into a single file for client download.
[src:rollup/minification-programming] JavaScript source maps can make code readable and debuggable even after it has been combined and minified.
[src:rollup/module-bundler] A **module bundler** is a software development tool that takes multiple source files and their dependencies (*modules*) and combines them into one or more output files called *bundles*.
[src:rollup/module-bundler] Module bundlers are commonly used in front-end web development to package JavaScript, CSS and other assets for efficient delivery to web browsers.
[src:rollup/module-bundler] Module bundlers typically start from one or more entry points and build a dependency graph of all imported modules before producing the final bundles, often applying optimisations such as minification and tree shaking.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] In computing, **tree shaking** is a dead code elimination technique that is applied when optimizing code.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] Often contrasted with traditional single-library dead code elimination techniques common to minifiers, tree shaking eliminates unused functions from across the bundle by starting at the entry point and only including functions that may be executed.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] It is succinctly described as "live code inclusion".
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] Dead code elimination in dynamic languages is a much harder problem than in static languages.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] The idea of a "treeshaker" originated in LISP in the 1990s.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] The idea is that all possible execution flows of a program can be represented as a tree of function calls, so that functions that are never called can be eliminated.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] The next wave of popularity of the term is attributed to Rich Harris's Rollup project developed in 2015.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] The popularity of tree shaking in JavaScript is based on the fact that in contrast to CommonJS modules, ECMAScript 6 module loading is static and thus the whole dependency tree can be deduced by statically parsing the syntax tree.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] Thus tree shaking becomes an easy problem.
[src:rollup/tree-shaking] However, tree shaking does not only apply at the import/export level: it can also work at the statement level, depending on the implementation.
[src:rollup/tutorial] The easiest way to use Rollup is via the Command Line Interface (or CLI).
[src:rollup/tutorial] For now, we'll install it globally (later on we'll learn how to install it locally to your project so that your build process is portable, but don't worry about that yet).
[src:rollup/tutorial] Because no arguments were passed, Rollup prints usage instructions.
[src:rollup/tutorial] This is the same as running `rollup --help`, or `rollup -h`.
[src:rollup/tutorial] The `-f` option (short for `--format`) specifies what kind of bundle we're creating — in this case, CommonJS (which will run in Node.js).
[src:rollup/tutorial] You've created your first bundle with Rollup.
[src:rollup/tutorial] So far, so good, but as we start adding more options it becomes a bit of a nuisance to type out the command.
[src:rollup/tutorial] To save repeating ourselves, we can create a config file containing all the options we need.
[src:rollup/tutorial] A config file is written in JavaScript and is more flexible than the raw CLI.
[src:rollup/tutorial] When working within teams or distributed environments it can be wise to add Rollup as a *local* dependency.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Installing Rollup locally prevents the requirement that multiple contributors install Rollup separately as an extra step, and ensures that all contributors are using the same version of Rollup.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Once installed, it's common practice to add a single build script to `package.json`, providing a convenient command for all contributors. e.g.
[src:rollup/tutorial] So far, we've created a simple bundle from an entry point and a module imported via a relative path.
[src:rollup/tutorial] As you build more complex bundles, you'll often need more flexibility – importing modules installed with NPM, compiling code with Babel, working with JSON files and so on.
[src:rollup/tutorial] For that, we use *plugins*, which change the behaviour of Rollup at key points in the bundling process.
[src:rollup/tutorial] A list of awesome plugins is maintained on the Rollup Awesome List.
[src:rollup/tutorial] For this tutorial, we'll use @rollup/plugin-json, which allows Rollup to import data from a JSON file.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Some plugins can also be applied specifically to some outputs.
[src:rollup/tutorial] See plugin hooks for the technical details of what output-specific plugins can do.
[src:rollup/tutorial] In a nut-shell, those plugins can only modify code after the main analysis of Rollup has completed.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Rollup will warn if an incompatible plugin is used as an output-specific plugin.
[src:rollup/tutorial] One possible use-case is minification of bundles to be consumed in a browser.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Let us extend the previous example to provide a minified build together with the non-minified one.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Edit your `rollup.config.mjs` file to add a second minified output.
[src:rollup/tutorial] This format wraps the code so that it can be consumed via a `script` tag in the browser while avoiding unwanted interactions with other code.
[src:rollup/tutorial] As we have an export, we need to provide the name of a global variable that will be created by our bundle so that other code can access our export via this variable.
[src:rollup/tutorial] For code splitting, there are cases where Rollup splits code into chunks automatically, like dynamic loading or multiple entry points, and there is a way to explicitly tell Rollup which modules to split into separate chunks via the `output.manualChunks` option.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Rollup will use the dynamic import to create a separate chunk that is only loaded on demand.
[src:rollup/tutorial] This will create a folder `dist` containing two files, `main.js` and `chunk-[hash].js`, where `[hash]` is a content based hash string.
[src:rollup/tutorial] You can supply your own naming patterns by specifying the `output.chunkFileNames` and `output.entryFileNames` options.
[src:rollup/tutorial] You can still run your code as before with the same output, albeit a little slower as loading and parsing of `./foo.js` will only commence once we call the exported function for the first time.
[src:rollup/tutorial] This is useful if you want to load and parse expensive features only once they are used.
[src:rollup/tutorial] A different use for code-splitting is the ability to specify several entry points that share some dependencies.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Notice how both entry points import the same shared chunk.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Rollup will never duplicate code and instead create additional chunks to only ever load the bare minimum necessary.
[src:rollup/tutorial] Again, passing the `--dir` option will write the files to disk.
[src:rollup/tutorial] You can build the same code for the browser via native ES modules, an AMD loader or SystemJS.
[src:rollup/tutorial] See rollup-starter-code-splitting for an example on how to set up a web app that uses native ES modules on browsers that support them with a fallback to SystemJS if necessary.
